{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659585"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:12:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:12:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20875"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20875"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100374"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13750"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82778"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"7614"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11579"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33110"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100374"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe accurate duplication of genetic material is essential during cell division to ensure proper transmission of genetic information to daughter cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the process of DNA replication in human cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Telomerase is required for replication of all chromosomal DNA","DNA synthesis occurs in the 3\u0027 to 5\u0027 direction on both strands","DNA replication follows a semiconservative model","Both DNA strands are synthesised continuously","DNA polymerase can initiate synthesis without RNA primers"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct description is that \u003Cstrong\u003EDNA replication follows a semiconservative model\u003C/strong\u003E. This fundamental principle describes how each newly formed DNA molecule contains one original parental strand paired with one newly synthesised complementary strand. During replication, the DNA double helix unwinds, and each original strand serves as a template for the assembly of complementary nucleotides according to base-pairing rules (adenine with thymine, guanine with cytosine).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamining why the other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETelomerase is required for replication of all chromosomal DNA\u003C/strong\u003E - Telomerase functions specifically at chromosome ends (telomeres) to prevent their progressive shortening during replication. The majority of DNA replication is performed by DNA polymerases, with telomerase having a specialised role only at telomeres.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDNA synthesis occurs in the 3\u0027 to 5\u0027 direction on both strands\u003C/strong\u003E - DNA polymerases exclusively synthesise DNA in the 5\u0027 to 3\u0027 direction. Since the two DNA strands are antiparallel, this directional constraint results in different replication mechanisms for each strand at the replication fork.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth DNA strands are synthesised continuously\u003C/strong\u003E - The antiparallel structure of DNA combined with the 5\u0027 to 3\u0027 synthesis requirement means only the leading strand can be synthesised continuously. The lagging strand must be synthesised discontinuously as Okazaki fragments that are subsequently joined by DNA ligase.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDNA polymerase can initiate synthesis without RNA primers\u003C/strong\u003E - DNA polymerases cannot initiate DNA synthesis de novo. They require a free 3\u0027-OH group provided by RNA primers, which are synthesised by primase, to begin adding nucleotides.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErrors in DNA replication machinery can lead to genomic instability and mutations, potentially contributing to various diseases including developmental disorders and cancer. The semiconservative nature of replication ensures genetic continuity while allowing for the occasional beneficial mutations that drive evolution.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["DNA replication follows a semiconservative model where each original strand serves as a template for a new complementary strand.","DNA polymerases can only synthesise DNA in the 5\u0027 to 3\u0027 direction and require RNA primers to initiate replication.","The leading strand is synthesised continuously while the lagging strand forms as Okazaki fragments that are later joined by DNA ligase."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease; p. 15-16"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82778"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20875"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82778"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-25T16:02:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-25T16:05:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13750"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100374"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data"